IP does not establish a connection with the destination before sending the packet.
There is no control information such as synchronisations and acknowledgements needed.
The destination will receive the packet when it arrives without any pre-notifiications sent by the IP.
If there is a need for connection-oriented traffic, other protocols will handle it, typically the TCP at the transport layer.
IP does not guarantee delivery of the packet.
IP has reduced overhead as there is no mechanism to resend data that is not received.
IP does not know if the other device is operational or if it has received the packet.
IP does not concern itself with the type of frame needed at the data link layer and the media type at the physical layer.
3 Types of Routes in a Router's Routing Table
- Routes are automatically added by the router, provided the interface is active and has addressing.
- Routes the router does not have a direct connection to. They may be learned either:
Dynamically - by using a routing protocol to have routers share information with each other.
- This forwards all traffic to a specific direction when there is not a match in the routing table.
Maintain up-to-date information by enabling routers to regularly exchange information with their neighbours.
Choose the best path to the destination.
They can find a new best path when there is a change in topology.
Routers can also share static default routes with each other.
Subnetting reduces overall network traffic and improves network performance.
Subenetting reduces the number of devices affected by abnormal broadcast traffic.
Since ARP requests are received and processed by every device on the network, excessive ARP requests can cause a reduction in network performance.
ARP replies can be spoofed by a threat actor to perform ARP poisoning attack.
Enterprise level switches include mitigation techniques to protect against ARP attacks.
